With a week to go it seems highly unlikely a ninth country will cross the 100,000 deaths mark, but still accounting for the slim possibility a country significantly revises their numbers. I continue to examine Turkey, which is experiencing a major surge. They have had 4.5 million COVID cases, but only 37,329 deaths from COVID. Unless Turkey has some new medical technology to respond to COVID or a genetic resilience to the virus they should have a death count significantly higher, probably above 100,000. But, the rules are the rules for these projections. I will slowly move towards 100% "7 or 8" over the next week.

Currently there are eight countries with more than 100,000 COVID deaths. So, the question is, will any other country cross that threshold in the next week and a halfish? The closest would appear to be Germany (81,382) and Spain (77,364). Either country would have to see a major surge in COVID deaths in the next week to cross the threshold, which is probably highly unlikely. Need to also account for the possibility that the true number of COVID deaths is revised in a county over the next week (I am looking at you Turkey).
Already at 8 countries

Numerous countries throughout the world lack the health-related resources to deal with COVID-19 and it's consequences, and some are so in need that they cannot provide adequate testing for large swathes of the population. Right now, it is suspected that thousands of people in these nations are dying and aren't even getting recorded because some of these countries lack the means to even log those deaths. Additionally, these nations are last in line to receive the vaccine, which will leave their rates of infection climbing ever higher.[1] Consequently, I predict that there is a 100% chance that 9 or more nations will have 100,000 or more deaths attributed to COVID-19 as of April 30th.

Final forecast. Updating from 0/0/0/97/3. It will be 8 countries: US, Brazil, Mexico, India, UK, Italy, Russia, France. They're all already there, and for any other countries to break 100k we'd need one of those retroactive updates, where a big pile of data is suddenly dumped onto the system. Trouble is, the size of the update would have to be 5-10x larger than any such dumps that have occurred in the past. In all cases except Germany and Spain (less likely to have such dumps), the backlog would have to be 50% or more of ALL deaths so far. Plus it would have to happen in the next 11 days.

Para realizar esta predicción, busque información acerca de la cantidad de muertes por coronavirus en distintos países, con lo que encontré una lista con los países con más muertes atribuidas al coronavirus. Dentro de esta lista, hay 7 países que ya tienen más de 100.000 muertes, por lo tanto, con esta información ya se que van a haber 7 o más países. Además, el octavo país con más muertes, Francia, tiene 99.135 muertes y al día de hoy (13 de abril), sumaron 385 muertes, por lo que es muy probable que a fin de mes ya hayan superado las 100.000 muertes, teniendo así 8 países en la lista. El noveno país con más muertes por coronavirus es Alemania, que registra 78.796 muertes, habiendo sumado 296 al día de hoy. Le siguen España con 76.5255 y Colombia con 66.156 muertes. De esta forma, veo muy dificil que puedan haber 9 o más países con más de 100.000 muertes, ya que, para el caso de Alemania (que se asoma como el noveno país), si tuviera una tasa de 300 muertes diarias por 18 días, se sumarían un poco más de 5.000 muertes, haciendo imposible que se llegue a un total de 100.000. Con esto, mi pronóstico es que si o si van a haber 7 u 8 países. Datos extraídos de Wikipedia, The New York Times y JHU CSSE COVID-19 DATA

With 23 days remaining for this question's tallying to close - 7 countries have already crossed the threshold of 100k deaths according to the WHO: US, Brazil, Mexico, India, UK, Italy, Russia. France is a few thousand away from crossing (currently @ ~97k) and currently has a 7 day death rate average of 276, which if maintained would push it above 100k within the stated timeframe (far earlier). Given that France is going through another wave of infection, reaching this number of deaths seems all but certain given past patterns of covid surges. The countries with the next two highest death tolls - Germany @ 77k and Spain @ 75 k - would need their average death rates for the next 23 days to increase by a factor of 9.5x and 12.4x respectively to cross the 100k threshold. Given they both seem to be in transmission plateaus (new cases / capita), this appears highly unlikely. Therefore, by the end of April the total number of countries with more than 100k reported covid deaths would be 7 (current number) + france, for a total of 8.

Leaving a low outside chance for uptick in cases there or in Colombia or Iran which is starting to see an uptick in deaths reported.

The rise across Europe is a concern (https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/mar/17/europe-at-the-start-of-a-third-wave-of-covid-experts-warn), however the number of deaths required is extremely high. Poland would need around 2,000 per day, a number not even reached by the UK at its peak. Germany would need the best part of 1,000 cases per day, similar to its peak. That would represent a catastrophically poor performance over the next month, especially given that vaccines have been rolled out to the most vulnerable (https://www.statista.com/statistics/1195560/coronavirus-covid-19-vaccinations-number-germany) and the weather is improving. Is there a chance that Germany or another breaks the 100,000 mark? Yes. Either by a seriously unfortunate event or, arguably more likely, a nation changes how it has counted the deaths retrospectively and the numbers jump up by a significant amount. There is a chance, but I don't see it as a 1% chance given how far into the pandemic we are and I've not heard of a single country change methods retrospectively since the UK (https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-data-idUSKBN29J2TH). Most interestingly, that only changed numbers by up to 6,000, no nearly enough to push any of the remaining countries to 100,000.

Passage of time

Germany is the only question. Germany's case growth is currently the mirror image of its case decline from winter. If it continues this way, Germany will probably see at most an additional number of deaths that is approximately the same as the number of deaths due to cases from Feb. 10 backwards 32 days to Jan. 9, inclusive, modified by the higher case fatality rate for B.1.1.7. With an approximately 3 week lag in deaths, this translates to the deaths from Jan. 30 through March 3. Germany added 15.0k deaths between Jan. 9 and March 3. However, B.1.1.7 is more deadly (30% to 50%?) than ancestral strains, so the deaths could be a bit higher. Note that many deaths can be expected to increase dramatically soon, because cases already went up, vaccination rates are low (albeit concentrated among seniors), and so, the deaths are already baked in. Germany's deaths currently stand at 76.1k. Even with incredible exponential growth in cases and greater case fatality rates due to B.1.1.7, it's probably not possible for Germany to reach 100k cases by April 30.

Update: I realized that elevated deaths in the second half of April in Germany will likely not be sufficient to "make up for" low death levels through mid April. Now through the end of April is unlikely to see an average of 700 cases/day, based on Germany's experience in the fall and winter, even if cases grow exponentially and quickly.

Germany is the only question. If their case numbers continue to increase, they will likely reach more than 100k deaths by the end of April. Case numbers are currently rising at a rate corresponding to doubling about every 2 weeks. If cases continue to rise for the next 2 weeks, then the deaths will follow with a 3 week lag. Deaths are at 76,303 now, with 34 days to go. That means if there is an average of 697 deaths/day, deaths will exceed 100k by April 30. Right now, there are about 200 deaths/day. Daily deaths will likely be double that, increasing and accelerating by mid April. Then the second half of April could have death rates over 1000/day.

Russia appears almost certain to push the total to 7 countries. France will probably follow. This then becomes a question of will Germany (required death rate ~540 per day, current ~200 and dropping) or Spain (rdr ~560, cdr ~100 and falling). From a quick scan, no other countries appear to threaten this threshold. The new rise in cases across central Europe (https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-56340161) is a concern, eg. the deaths in Czechia are on a significant rise. However Poland would need a period not unlike the UK suffered in the first 50 days of 2021 and from a smaller population. Czechia would need to have a period worse than any seen so far, and from a far smaller population (80,000 deaths in 50 days would represent 0.8% of the total population). (RU also exercises drastic underreporting, hard to tell if this will change until end of April.) Will there be a 9th? Germany is, at first sight, the obvious candidate. With, from now on, 468 deaths per day (84% of February average of 560 /d so far), GE would pass 100k on April 30. However, this is *unlikely*, due to - vaccine rollout protecting most vulnerable demographics - strict German policies - warmer season ahead So, after forecasting this question 25 times, I am resting my case today by making two predictions: 1) 7-8 countries: 100% 2) This is my last forecast for this question Of course, I might err in both points, but I feel confident with this question for the first time since October….

UK has turned. Italy is too close to avoid this unfortunate milestone. The other three concerns are France, Russia and Germany. For France and Germany, their weather over the next 7/10 days will be very poor. Depending on how they count deaths, that could impact. France is holding steady and I expect the current death rate (~400 per day) to hold through February. However they only need to average under 265 per day over the full period to come under 100,000 deaths. Over the remaining 60 days of the time period that would be 223 deaths per day. Their vaccine roll out has been slow (and frankly strange at times), but they have a good chance of having low death rates in mid-late March through April. Their cases counts are not encouraging however. Requirement for weekly count at 1st March: 1800. Germany should avoid the 100,000. They are currently at ~640 deaths per day and need to average 466 per day for the entire period. On current pace Germany will be at 460 deaths per day in another ~3 weeks. Even assuming a bad February, they should be able to manage to drop below the 460 deaths per day mark by the start of March. I will be looking at the weekly figure for 1st March with interest. If it is below 3,220 then "9 or more" will become very unlikely. Cases also dropping. Russia is most likely of the three to break the 100,000 barrier. It has recorded ~500 deaths per day for the past 7 days. It needs to average below 285 per day for the next 83 days to fail to break 100,000. The recent week on week decrease is significant and encouraging, but of course one cannot extrapolate too much from a single weekly count. it is less distinct in the daily figures, for instance. However the case rates are falling ahead of the deaths! Their vaccines seem decent and we should expect improvement. Russia should end up very close to 100,000. 1st March crucial weekly figure: 2,000.

Comparing it to Brazil which took 87 days to move to get to 1MM cases, while Argentina took 202 days. Their pace is 2.3x slower. I agree with both @smitch15 and @Bobbiekar52 (mostly). It's probably too big a jump to100k for medium-sized populations or smaller. Going by large population size, Mexico and Russia are the current stand-outs. Yet the latter is plainly under-reporting. Ditto China. Other than a seismic political change in either nation that is likely to remain true until April. And other nations with large populations either have poor quality health care systems that will under-report (Indonesia, Nigeria, Pakistan etc.) or superb systems that have handled the pandemic very well (Japan, Germany). A medium-sized nation could lose control of their outbreak, but that does not necessarily mean deaths will again increase at the same rate. With the medical knowledge gained this year, second wave death rates in Europe are not (so far) spiking as high as in, for example, Italy in March-April. My stand-out concern is Argentina. Its death rate tracks its exponential increase in cases. It needs to be watched carefully.

First things first, it is very clear that Mexico will reach 100k deaths, so this question will almost certainly resolve >=4. There have been about 200 days since COVID became a global pandemic and there are about 200 days until this question resolves. The easiest way to predict, then, is to assume countries ability to control the coronavirus is unchanged, and just double their deaths over the past 200 days as a prediction. That gives a prediction of 4, but a lot of countries (11 I think) reach around 60k-70k deaths.

Mexico is at 87K as of 10-24-20, so it is almost certain to reach higher. The U.K is at44K. There are several countries around 30K level (France, Spain, Iran, Peru, Argentina, Russia, Columbia) that, after winter and with potential greater re-opening, will have many more cases and potentially more deaths (mitigated by better treatment methods). It is a slight stretch at the moment to think all will reach this level given better care and potentially inadequate reporting, but it is possible several countries might. Then if it hits the densely populated countries hard (Bangladesh, Indonesia, Phillipines) and is mismanaged by places such as South Africa, they have a small chance to join the 100K club. It is unlikely that a vaccine, while it may be developed, will be widely available by then globally.

Five are effectively guaranteed (current three plus Mexico and Argentina). Then there are a handful of others (at least five) that—based on current surges—I'd put in the 60% realm, followed by another handful of 4-5 that I'd put in the 20-40% realm. Some rough mathing on the probability that at least one or two of these other groups break 100k threshold, along with my go-to "it's usually worse than we think it's going to be" heuristic for COVID questions, puts me in the zone of this current forecast.
